      <div align="center">
        <center>
        <table border="0" cellpadding="7" cellspacing="7" style="border-collapse: collapse" bordercolor="#111111" width="97%" id="AutoNumber1" height="335">
          <tr>
            <td width="100%" height="335" valign="top">
            <p class="MsoNormal"><b>
            <span lang="EN-US" style="font-size: 13.5pt; color: #570E0A">The 
            Cider</span></b></p>
            <p class="MsoNormal" style="text-align: justify; line-height: 120%">
            <span lang="EN-US" style="font-size: 10.0pt; line-height: 120%; font-family: Arial; color: #570E0A">
            “According to the Argentine Food Code, what is understood as the 
            generic denomination of Cider or Genuine Cider, is the drink that is 
            obtained by normal alcohol fermentation of fresh apple juice, 
            industrially healthy and clear, with or without the addition of 
            pears, in a proportion no superior than 10%”.</span></p>
            <h1 style="line-height:120%">
            <span lang="EN-US" style="font-size: 10.0pt; line-height: 120%; font-family: Arial; color: #570E0A">
            Its Name</span></h1>
            <p class="MsoNormal" style="text-align: justify; line-height: 120%">
            <span lang="EN-US" style="font-size: 10.0pt; line-height: 120%; font-family: Arial; color: #570E0A">
            The origin if the word cider, comes from the Greek <b>“sikera”.</b> 
            In Latin is passes as sicera and in Asturian it begins to be 
            pronounced as <b>“sizra”</b> and finally in Spanish “<b>sidra”. </b>
            In middle English it became <b>“sidre”.</b></span></p>
            <h1 style="line-height:120%">
            <span lang="EN-US" style="font-size: 10.0pt; line-height: 120%; font-family: Arial; color: #570E0A">
            History </span></h1>
            <p class="MsoNormal" style="text-align: justify; line-height: 120%">
            <span lang="EN-US" style="font-size: 10.0pt; line-height: 120%; font-family: Arial; color: #570E0A">
            There are numerous texts throughout history that name cider and the
            <b>orchards</b> (apple tree plantations), but there is really no 
            certifiable documentation about the origin of cider, except for the 
            written by different authors, which assure that cider was already 
            known by the <b>Hebrew</b>, the <b>Egyptians </b>and the <b>Greek</b>.<b>
            </b></span></p>
            <p class="MsoNormal" style="text-align: justify; line-height: 120%">
            <b>
            <span lang="EN-US" style="font-size: 10.0pt; line-height: 120%; font-family: Arial; color: #570E0A">
            Plinio </span></b>
            <span lang="EN-US" style="font-size: 10.0pt; line-height: 120%; font-family: Arial; color: #570E0A">
            (23-79 d.c.) mentions drinks of pears and apples &quot; <i>e piris 
            malorunque omnibus generibus </i>&quot;, cites apple wine and says that &quot;<i>… 
            it’s the territory typical drink”</i></span></p>
            <p class="MsoNormal" style="text-align: justify; line-height: 120%">
            <b>
            <span lang="EN-US" style="font-size: 10.0pt; line-height: 120%; font-family: Arial; color: #570E0A">
            Estrabon</span></b><span lang="EN-US" style="font-size: 10.0pt; line-height: 120%; font-family: Arial; color: #570E0A">, 
            approximately 60 years before Christ, writes that the astures also 
            use cider, since they have little wine <i>&quot;zytho&nbsp; etiam utuntur, 
            vini parum habent&quot;</i></span></p>
            <p class="MsoNormal" style="text-align: justify; line-height: 120%">
            <b>
            <span lang="EN-US" style="font-size: 10.0pt; line-height: 120%; font-family: Arial; color: #570E0A">
            Palladius </span></b>
            <span lang="EN-US" style="font-size: 10.0pt; line-height: 120%; font-family: Arial; color: #570E0A">
            shows us that in the 3rd Century the Romans prepared pear wines and 
            even gives details of its production.</span></p>
            <p class="MsoNormal" style="text-align: justify; line-height: 120%">
            <span lang="EN-US">&nbsp;</span></p>
            <p class="MsoNormal" style="line-height: 120%"><b>
            <span lang="EN-US" style="font-size: 13.5pt; line-height: 120%; color: #570E0A">
            Cider in Argentina</span></b></p>
            <p class="MsoBodyText" style="text-align:justify">
            <span lang="EN-US" style="font-size: 10.0pt; font-family: Arial; color: #570E0A">
            In our country, the first cider production dates back to 1908 in the 
            Parana Delta with apples of the region.</span></p>
            <p class="MsoNormal" style="text-align: justify; line-height: 120%">
            <span lang="EN-US" style="font-size: 10.0pt; line-height: 120%; font-family: Arial; color: #570E0A">
            Until the year 1932 remote production tests were effectuated by the 
            Island Plant, who was the first entity that produced cider in an 
            industrial scale of acceptable quality.</span></p>
            <p class="MsoNormal" style="text-align: justify; line-height: 120%">
            <span lang="EN-US" style="font-size: 10.0pt; line-height: 120%; font-family: Arial; color: #570E0A">
            In the country there are 15 producing companies. Seven industrial 
            plants are located in Mendoza (Tunuyan), seven in the Alto Valley of 
            Rio Negro and one in Calingasta, San Juan, being these the most 
            popular industry production zones. (juice, fresh apples, cider).</span></p>
            <p class="MsoNormal" style="text-align: justify; line-height: 120%">
            <span lang="EN-US" style="font-size: 10.0pt; line-height: 120%; font-family: Arial; color: #570E0A">
            Without entering in the description of the diverse apple varieties, 
            it is enough to say that in practice they are divided into 3 
            categories:</span></p>
            <p class="MsoNormal" style="line-height: 120%">
            <span lang="EN-US" style="font-size: 10.0pt; line-height: 120%; font-family: Arial; color: #570E0A">
            &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <b>-</b> Sweet Apples</span></p>
            <p class="MsoNormal" style="line-height: 120%">
            <span lang="EN-US" style="font-size: 10.0pt; line-height: 120%; font-family: Arial; color: #570E0A">
            &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <b>- </b>Sour Apples </span></p>
            <p class="MsoNormal" style="line-height: 120%">
            <span lang="EN-US" style="font-size: 10.0pt; line-height: 120%; font-family: Arial; color: #570E0A">
            &nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; <b>- </b>Bitter Apples</span></p>
            <p class="MsoNormal" style="text-align: justify; line-height: 120%">
            <span lang="EN-US" style="font-size: 10.0pt; line-height: 120%; font-family: Arial; color: #570E0A">
            To produce good cider, the sour apples are excluded and it is 
            recommended not to introduce more than the eight of tenth part of&nbsp; 
            these in the total weight of the fruit that is crushed</span></p>
            <p class="MsoNormal" style="text-align: justify; line-height: 120%">
            <span lang="EN-US" style="font-size: 10.0pt; line-height: 120%; font-family: Arial; color: #570E0A">
            Regarding the others, they are mixed under variable conditions 
            according to the perfume and bouquet they posses. Generally when it 
            is desired that a cider is well preserved, it is necessary to 
            increase the proportion of bitter apples, if it regards a sweet 
            cider of immediate consumption, the quality of sweet apples in the 
            mix can be elevated to 2/3. When the ripening is produced under 
            unfavorable conditions, it is favorable to increase the proportion 
            of bitter apples.</span></p>
            <h2><span lang="EN-US" style="font-size: 10.0pt; color: #570E0A">
            Physicochemical characteristics</span></h2>
            <p class="MsoNormal" style="text-align: justify">
            <span lang="EN-US" style="font-size: 10.0pt; font-family: Arial; color: #570E0A">
            Alcohol--------------------------------------- 4º to 7º GL</span></p>
            <p class="MsoNormal" style="text-align: justify">
            <span lang="EN-US" style="font-size: 10.0pt; font-family: Arial; color: #570E0A">
            Total acidity ---------------------------------- 4,5 g/lts. of 
            Tartaric ac.</span></p>
            <p class="MsoNormal" style="text-align: justify">
            <span lang="EN-US" style="font-size: 10.0pt; font-family: Arial; color: #570E0A">
            Volatile acidity--------------------------------- up to 1 g/lts of 
            Acetic acidity</span></p>
            <p class="MsoNormal" style="line-height: 120%">
            <span lang="EN-US" style="font-size: 10.0pt; line-height: 120%; font-family: Arial; color: #570E0A">
            Sugar:&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; 80 grs per lt</span></p>
            <p class="MsoNormal" style="text-align: justify">
            <span lang="EN-US" style="font-size: 10.0pt; font-family: Arial; color: #570E0A">
            Dry extract--------------------------------- superior to 16 g/lts</span></p>
            <p class="MsoNormal" style="text-align: justify">
            <span lang="EN-US" style="font-size: 10.0pt; font-family: Arial; color: #570E0A">
            Ashes--------------------------------------- over 1,8 g/lts</span></p>
            <p class="MsoNormal" style="text-align: justify">
            <span lang="EN-US" style="font-size: 10.0pt; font-family: Arial; color: #570E0A">
            Sulfur dioxide total&nbsp; ---------------------- up to 150 mg/lts</span></p>
            <p class="MsoNormal" style="text-align: justify">
            <span lang="EN-US" style="font-size: 10.0pt; font-family: Arial; color: #570E0A">
            Sulfur dioxide free ---------------------- from 20 to 100 mg/lts</span></p>
            <p class="MsoNormal" style="text-align: justify">
            <span lang="EN-US" style="font-size: 10.0pt; font-family: Arial; color: #570E0A">
            Sorbic acid &nbsp;(as sorbate) ------------------ 250 mg/lts</span></p>
            <p class="MsoNormal" style="text-align: justify">
            <span lang="EN-US" style="font-size: 10.0pt; font-family: Arial; color: #570E0A">
            pH------------------------------------------- 3,1 a 3,9</span></p>
            <p class="MsoNormal" style="line-height: 120%">
            <span lang="EN-US" style="font-size: 10.0pt; line-height: 120%; font-family: Arial; color: #570E0A">
            Turbity:&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; less than &nbsp;1 U.T.N (nefelometric turbity unit)</span></p>
            <p class="MsoNormal" style="text-align: justify">
            <span lang="EN-US" style="font-size: 10.0pt; font-family: Arial; color: #570E0A">
            CO<sub>2 </sub>saturation: &nbsp;4 atm (the same that a charmat method 
            champagne would have) </span></p>
            <p class="MsoNormal" style="text-align: justify">
            <span lang="EN-US" style="font-size: 10.0pt; font-family: Arial; color: #570E0A">
            Poliphenols total content &gt; 1,5 gr. / l. expressed as tanic</span></p>
            <p class="MsoNormal" style="text-align: justify">
            <span lang="EN-US" style="font-size: 10.0pt; font-family: Arial; color: #570E0A">
            Sweetening with sugar (sucrose) and corn syrup is allowed (JMAF).</span></p>
            <p class="MsoNormal" style="text-align: justify">
            <span lang="EN-US" style="font-size: 10.0pt; font-family: Arial; color: #570E0A">
            Depending on the type of sweetener used:</span></p>
            <p class="MsoNormal" style="text-align: justify">
            <span lang="EN-US" style="font-size: 10.0pt; font-family: Arial; color: #570E0A">
            &nbsp;Full = only sugar</span></p>
            <p class="MsoNormal" style="text-align: justify">
            <span lang="EN-US" style="font-family: Arial">Partial </span>
            <span lang="EN-US" style="font-size: 10.0pt; font-family: Arial; color: #570E0A">
            = sugar and corn syrup</span></p>
            <p class="MsoNormal" style="text-align: justify"><b>
            <span lang="EN-US" style="font-size: 10.0pt; font-family: Arial; color: #570E0A">
            TYPES OF CIDER</span></b></p>
            <p class="MsoNormal" style="text-align: justify; text-indent: -14.2pt; margin-left: 14.2pt">
            <span lang="EN-US" style="font-size: 10.0pt; font-family: Arial; color: #570E0A">
            ·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; gasified industrially with bulk CO2</span></p>
            <p class="MsoNormal" style="text-align: justify; text-indent: -14.2pt; margin-left: 14.2pt">
            <span lang="EN-US" style="font-size: 10.0pt; font-family: Arial; color: #570E0A">
            ·&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; sparkling &nbsp;(champagne like)&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; </span></p>
            <p class="MsoNormal"><b>
            <span lang="EN-US" style="font-size: 10.0pt; font-family: Arial; color: #570E0A">
            • <u>Cider:</u></span></b><span lang="EN-US" style="font-size: 10.0pt; font-family: Arial; color: #570E0A"> 
            &nbsp;is the drink resultant from the total or partial alcoholic 
            fermentation of fresh apples and its must.</span></p>
            <p class="MsoNormal">
            <span lang="EN-US" style="font-size: 10.0pt; font-family: Arial; color: #570E0A">
            The minimum alcohol content acquired must be 5% in volume.</span></p>
            <p class="MsoNormal">
            <span lang="EN-US" style="font-size: 10.0pt; font-family: Arial; color: #570E0A">
            It is denominated dry cider when it contains less than 30g/l of 
            sugar; semidry between 30 and 50g/l and sweet when it contains from 
            50 g/l to its maximum limit which is 80 g/l.</span></p>
            <p class="MsoNormal"><b>
            <span lang="EN-US" style="font-size: 10.0pt; font-family: Arial; color: #570E0A">
            • <u>Natural Cider</u></span></b><span lang="EN-US" style="font-size: 10.0pt; font-family: Arial; color: #570E0A">:
            <b><u>:</u></b>&nbsp; is the drink resultant from the total or partial 
            alcoholic fermentation of fresh apples and its must, produced 
            following the traditional methods, without sugar additives, it 
            contains carbon gas originated from within.</span></p>
            <p>
            <span lang="EN-US" style="font-size: 10.0pt; font-family: Arial; color: #570E0A">
            The minimum alcohol content acquired is of 5% in volume</span></p>
            <p class="MsoNormal" style="line-height: 120%; text-autospace: none" align="left">
            <span lang="es"><font size="2" color="#570E0A"><b>
            <span style="font-family: Arial">Cider Production</span></b></font></span><font color="#570E0A" size="2"><span lang="ES" style="line-height: 120%; font-family: Arial">
            </span></font></p>
            <p class="MsoNormal" style="line-height: 120%; text-autospace: none" align="center">
            <img border="0" src="images/cadena-alimentaria.jpg"></p>
            <p class="MsoNormal" style="text-align: justify; line-height: 120%">
            <b>
            <span lang="EN-US" style="font-size: 10.0pt; line-height: 120%; font-family: Arial; color: #570E0A">
            HARVEST AND TRANSPORT</span></b></p>
            <p class="MsoBodyText2">
            <span lang="EN-US" style="font-size: 10.0pt; font-family: Arial; color: #570E0A">
            To obtain a maximum quality cider it is essential to begin with 
            looking after the raw material, the apple; for this it is necessary 
            to carry out a correct plantation applying the appropriate 
            techniques. Another important aspect is the harvest; this must be 
            done at the opportune time, previously effectuating the adequate 
            quality and hygiene controls. The apple must be healthy, mature and 
            with the right parameters.</span></p>
            <p class="MsoNormal" style="text-align: justify; line-height: 120%">
            <span lang="EN-US" style="font-size: 10.0pt; line-height: 120%; font-family: Arial; color: #570E0A">
            The transport to the plant must be done as soon as possible, to 
            avoid oxidations and over maturities. The process at the plant is 
            the following: </span></p>
            <h2>
            <span lang="EN-US" style="font-size: 10.0pt; color: #570E0A; text-transform: uppercase">
            Apple washing</span></h2>
            <p class="MsoNormal" style="text-align: justify; line-height: 120%">
            <span lang="EN-US" style="font-size: 10.0pt; line-height: 120%; font-family: Arial; color: #570E0A">
            Consists of eliminating the maximum quantity of strange substances 
            (Earth, residues, vegetables, etc….), as also the possible germs 
            that may be on the apples or the bodies before mentioned.</span></p>
            <p class="MsoNormal" style="text-align: justify; line-height: 120%">
            <b>
            <span lang="EN-US" style="font-size: 10.0pt; line-height: 120%; font-family: Arial; color: #570E0A">
            GRINDING&nbsp; </span></b></p>
            <p class="MsoNormal" style="text-align: justify; line-height: 120%">
            <span lang="EN-US" style="font-size: 10.0pt; line-height: 120%; font-family: Arial; color: #570E0A">
            The grinding is done by means of a hammer mill, rolls and/or blades, 
            adapting them always to the press requirements( fast extraction 
            system, between 2 and 4 hours; or slow like in the classic systems 
            that last three or four days) and the state of maturity (fruit 
            hardness or swelling). This way, the raw material is grinded, 
            turning it into a juicy paste that is pumped to short term storage 
            tolvas. These tolvas full of apple paste are manipulated to dosify 
            the paste for the presses. The juice extraction is done with 
            semi-continue hydraulic presses. The yields in juice are of 
            approximately between 70 and 75 lts per every 100 kgs of apples.
            </span></p>
            <p class="MsoNormal" style="text-align: justify; line-height: 120%">
            <span lang="EN-US" style="font-size: 10.0pt; line-height: 120%; font-family: Arial; color: #570E0A">
            To avoid contaminations of metals such as copper, iron, etc…. in the 
            must , the use of stainless steel is recommended , or the use of 
            special paint used in the food industry.</span></p>
            <h2>
            <span lang="EN-US" style="font-size: 10.0pt; color: #570E0A; text-transform: uppercase">
            MaceratiOn </span></h2>
            <p class="MsoNormal" style="line-height: 120%">
            <span lang="EN-US" style="font-size: 10.0pt; line-height: 120%; font-family: Arial; color: #570E0A">
            Recommendable in mixes or acid varieties and in hard apples. </span>
            </p>
            <h1 style="line-height:120%">
            <span lang="EN-US" style="font-size: 10.0pt; line-height: 120%; font-family: Arial; color: #570E0A; text-transform: uppercase">
            Pressing</span></h1>
            <p class="MsoNormal" style="text-align: justify; line-height: 120%">
            <span lang="EN-US" style="font-size: 10.0pt; line-height: 120%; font-family: Arial; color: #570E0A">
            If possible, all oxidations must be avoided during pressing. The 
            must cloudiness levels must be controlled especially throughout the 
            last presses. It is preferable to reduce the extraction yields to 
            having to correct possible alterations derived from press 
            contaminations. </span></p>
            <p class="MsoNormal" style="text-align: justify; line-height: 120%">
            <span lang="EN-US" style="font-size: 10.0pt; line-height: 120%; font-family: Arial; color: #570E0A">
            Corrections with blends of different broths to maintain a protected 
            pH, especially in the cases where the pH is higher than 3´5. As a 
            rule, never exceed 1´5g/l of malic acid. </span></p>
            <p class="MsoNormal" style="text-align: justify; line-height: 120%">
            <b>
            <span lang="EN-US" style="font-size: 10.0pt; line-height: 120%; font-family: Arial; color: #570E0A">
            JUICE TREATMENTS BEFORE FERMENTATION </span></b></p>
            <p class="MsoNormal" style="text-align: justify; line-height: 120%">
            <span lang="EN-US" style="font-size: 10.0pt; line-height: 120%; font-family: Arial; color: #570E0A">
            The juices obtained are sulphated with low dosis of SO2 (7 to 10 grs 
            hl of SO2) which re trasvased to separate them from their sediments, 
            in these conditions the selected yeast are placed to obtain better 
            fermentations and of a higher quality in scent and taste.</span></p>
            <h1 style="text-align:justify;line-height:120%">
            <span lang="EN-US" style="font-size: 10.0pt; line-height: 120%; font-family: Arial; color: #570E0A; text-transform: uppercase">
            Fermentation</span></h1>
            <p class="MsoNormal" style="text-align: justify; line-height: 120%">
            <span lang="EN-US" style="font-size: 10.0pt; line-height: 120%; font-family: Arial; color: #570E0A">
            The fermentation of the broth takes from 5 to 7 days, after which 
            the first separation from the sediments is done and the anhydride 
            sulphur is adjusted, with the purpose of starting the cleaning 
            process. </span></p>
            <p class="MsoNormal" style="text-align: justify; line-height: 120%">
            <span lang="EN-US" style="font-size: 10.0pt; line-height: 120%; font-family: Arial; color: #570E0A">
            Two phases must be seen here: </span></p>
            <p class="MsoNormal" style="text-align: justify; line-height: 120%">
            <b><i>
            <span lang="EN-US" style="font-size: 10.0pt; line-height: 120%; font-family: Arial; color: #570E0A">
            Tumultuous</span></i></b><span lang="EN-US" style="font-size: 10.0pt; line-height: 120%; font-family: Arial; color: #570E0A">, 
            in which the yeasts (Saccharomyces sp.) act on the must sugars 
            transforming them into alcohol and CO2. </span></p>
            <p class="MsoNormal" style="text-align: justify; line-height: 120%">
            <b><i>
            <span lang="EN-US" style="font-size: 10.0pt; line-height: 120%; font-family: Arial; color: #570E0A">
            Slow or malolactic</span></i></b><span lang="EN-US" style="font-size: 10.0pt; line-height: 120%; font-family: Arial; color: #570E0A">, 
            the bacteria act in the malic acid generating lactic acid and CO2.
            </span></p>
            <p class="MsoNormal" style="text-align: justify; line-height: 120%">
            <span lang="EN-US" style="font-size: 10.0pt; line-height: 120%; font-family: Arial; color: #570E0A">
            Generally The malolactic fermentation is produced once the 
            tumultuous one is done, but there are cases in which the malolactic 
            begins before the tumultuous is finished. </span></p>
            <p class="MsoNormal" style="text-align: justify; line-height: 120%">
            <span lang="EN-US" style="font-size: 10.0pt; line-height: 120%; font-family: Arial; color: #570E0A">
            It is recommended a temperature of 15-17ºC &nbsp;is maintained during the 
            tumultuous fermentation , and a temperature between 12-14ºC 
            &nbsp;throughout the malolactic fermentation. </span></p>
            <p class="MsoBodyText" style="text-align:justify">
            <span lang="EN-US" style="font-size: 10.0pt; font-family: Arial; color: #570E0A">
            The recipient must be filled up to 85-90% during the tumultuous 
            fermentation, and almost full during the malolactic fermentation. 
            Avoid the overflow of the must “txapela“ during the fermentation.
            </span></p>
            <p class="MsoBodyText2">
            <span lang="EN-US" style="font-size: 10.0pt; font-family: Arial; color: #570E0A">
            Throughout the tumultuous daily controls of must density and 
            temperature are carried out. The density value when out of the press 
            is approximately 1045-1055 and this will decrease as the 
            fermentation process progresses (tumultuous) down to 999-1001, 
            indicating the final stage of this phase. During this phase the 
            deposit will be kept with the lid over the top to avoid dust and 
            drosophilae (fruits mosquitoes) from getting in, but not closed so 
            that the CO2 generated can be evacuated. </span></p>
            <h1 style="line-height:120%">
            <span lang="EN-US" style="font-size: 10.0pt; line-height: 120%; font-family: Arial; color: #570E0A; text-transform: uppercase">
            DEPOSIT CLOSURE </span></h1>
            <p class="MsoBodyText2">
            <span lang="EN-US" style="font-size: 10.0pt; font-family: Arial; color: #570E0A">
            The deposit will be closed at the density of 1002-1004, filling it 
            completely with cider to avoid oxidations. </span></p>
            <h1 style="line-height:120%">
            <span lang="EN-US" style="font-size: 10.0pt; line-height: 120%; font-family: Arial; color: #570E0A; text-transform: uppercase">
            TRASVASING</span></h1>
            <p class="MsoBodyText2">
            <span lang="EN-US" style="font-size: 10.0pt; font-family: Arial; color: #570E0A">
            Separation of the cider fermentation sediments. The purpose of this 
            operation is to try and improve the microbiologic and chemical 
            stability of the cider. It is done in those cases in which some kind 
            of deviation is observed, be it in the analysis or tasting, taking 
            into account that it must always be done airtight, at low 
            temperature and if possible when the atmospheric pressure is high.
            </span></p>
            <p class="MsoNormal" style="text-align: justify; line-height: 120%">
            <b>
            <span lang="EN-US" style="font-size: 10.0pt; line-height: 120%; font-family: Arial; color: #570E0A">
            CLARIFICATION AND FILTRATION</span></b><span lang="EN-US" style="font-size: 10.0pt; line-height: 120%; font-family: Arial; color: #570E0A">
            </span></p>
            <p class="MsoBodyText3">
            <span lang="EN-US" style="font-size: 10.0pt; font-family: Arial; color: #570E0A">
            The clarification consists of carrying out two or three transvases, 
            and then by means of special clarifiers, (Bentonite, jelly, etc.) a 
            more effective clarity is achieved. Under these conditions, a final 
            and more profound clearing is done by means of diatomaceous earth 
            filters.</span></p>
            <h1 style="line-height:120%">
            <span lang="EN-US" style="font-size: 10.0pt; line-height: 120%; font-family: Arial; color: #570E0A; text-transform: uppercase">
            BOTTLING</span></h1>
            <p class="MsoBodyText2">
            <span lang="EN-US" style="font-size: 10.0pt; font-family: Arial; color: #570E0A">
            This will be done when the cider is below 1000 density value and if 
            the aromatic and taste qualities required of the natural quality 
            cider are found. As for its execution, the same transvasing criteria 
            will be followed, especially avoided oxidations and stirring the 
            cider the least possible. </span></p>
            <p class="MsoNormal" style="line-height: 120%">
            <span lang="EN-US" style="font-size: 10.0pt; line-height: 120%; font-family: Arial; color: #570E0A">
            It is recommended that the following are added: </span></p>
            <p class="MsoNormal" style="line-height: 120%">
            <span lang="EN-US" style="font-size: 10.0pt; line-height: 120%; font-family: Arial; color: #570E0A">
            10 gr. / hl. de acid ascorbic </span></p>
            <p class="MsoNormal" style="text-align: justify; line-height: 120%">
            <span lang="EN-US" style="font-size: 10.0pt; line-height: 120%; font-family: Arial; color: #570E0A">
            8 gr. / hl. de potassium met bisulphate.</span></p>
            <h2>
            <span lang="EN-US" style="font-size: 10.0pt; font-family: Arial; color: #570E0A">
            POURING</span></h2>
            <p class="MsoNormal" style="text-align: justify; line-height: 120%">
            <span lang="EN-US" style="font-size: 10.0pt; line-height: 120%; font-family: Arial; color: #570E0A">
            This is done so that the oxygen in the air mixes with the carbonic 
            that the cider has. This way, the organoleptic properties, acquire 
            relevant and significance.</span></p>
            <p class="MsoNormal" style="text-align: justify; line-height: 120%">
            <span lang="EN-US" style="font-size: 10.0pt; line-height: 120%; font-family: Arial; color: #570E0A">
            A little pungency is what the cider acquires when it is poured.</span></p>
            <p class="MsoNormal" style="text-align: justify; line-height: 120%">
            <span lang="EN-US" style="font-size: 10.0pt; line-height: 120%; font-family: Arial; color: #570E0A">
            The cider needs to air before being consumed and due to this is that 
            it needs to be poured from high, it is not just something merely 
            esthetic. Though in the past the height wasn’t so much due to the 
            reduced size of glasses, today with the current glasses, which are 
            of thin glass and with a height of approximately 12 cm, with 9 cm 
            rim and 7 cm base, the pouring height has increase up to a level 
            over the head, up to where the arm reaches.</span></p>
            <p class="MsoNormal" style="line-height: 120%"><b>
            <span lang="EN-US" style="font-size: 10.0pt; line-height: 120%; font-family: Arial; color: #570E0A">
            Decalogue of cider serving: </span></b></p>
            <p class="MsoNormal" style="text-align: justify; line-height: 120%">
            <b>
            <span lang="EN-US" style="font-size: 10.0pt; line-height: 120%; font-family: Arial; color: #570E0A">
            1º</span></b><span lang="EN-US" style="font-size: 10.0pt; line-height: 120%; font-family: Arial; color: #570E0A"> 
            The posture must be straight, without being rigid. </span></p>
            <p class="MsoNormal" style="text-align: justify; line-height: 120%">
            <b>
            <span lang="EN-US" style="font-size: 10.0pt; line-height: 120%; font-family: Arial; color: #570E0A">
            2º</span></b><span lang="EN-US" style="font-size: 10.0pt; line-height: 120%; font-family: Arial; color: #570E0A">The 
            arm that holds the bottle, stretched above the head. </span></p>
            <p class="MsoNormal" style="text-align: justify; line-height: 120%">
            <b>
            <span lang="EN-US" style="font-size: 10.0pt; line-height: 120%; font-family: Arial; color: #570E0A">
            3º</span></b><span lang="EN-US" style="font-size: 10.0pt; line-height: 120%; font-family: Arial; color: #570E0A"> 
            The arm that holds the glass stretched down low and toward the 
            center of the body. </span></p>
            <p class="MsoNormal" style="text-align: justify; line-height: 120%">
            <b>
            <span lang="EN-US" style="font-size: 10.0pt; line-height: 120%; font-family: Arial; color: #570E0A">
            4º</span></b><span lang="EN-US" style="font-size: 10.0pt; line-height: 120%; font-family: Arial; color: #570E0A"> 
            Once the bottle has been tilted to pour the liquid, it is held with 
            the index finger, the middle and ring fingers over the body part and 
            the thumb and little one on the base. </span></p>
            <p class="MsoNormal" style="text-align: justify; line-height: 120%">
            <b>
            <span lang="EN-US" style="font-size: 10.0pt; line-height: 120%; font-family: Arial; color: #570E0A">
            5º</span></b><span lang="EN-US" style="font-size: 10.0pt; line-height: 120%; font-family: Arial; color: #570E0A"> 
            The fingers that hold the bottle must not go beyond the same towards 
            the rim direction. </span></p>
            <p class="MsoNormal" style="text-align: justify; line-height: 120%">
            <b>
            <span lang="EN-US" style="font-size: 10.0pt; line-height: 120%; font-family: Arial; color: #570E0A">
            6º</span></b><span lang="EN-US" style="font-size: 10.0pt; line-height: 120%; font-family: Arial; color: #570E0A"> 
            The glass is held with the index thumb and index finger on the base 
            of the glass and the ring finger together with the little one held 
            in the palm of the hand. </span></p>
            <p class="MsoNormal" style="text-align: justify; line-height: 120%">
            <b>
            <span lang="EN-US" style="font-size: 10.0pt; line-height: 120%; font-family: Arial; color: #570E0A">
            7º </span></b>
            <span lang="EN-US" style="font-size: 10.0pt; line-height: 120%; font-family: Arial; color: #570E0A">
            The glass must not move from the center of the body, which means 
            that the cider bottle should look for the glass. </span></p>
            <p class="MsoNormal" style="text-align: justify; line-height: 120%">
            <b>
            <span lang="EN-US" style="font-size: 10.0pt; line-height: 120%; font-family: Arial; color: #570E0A">
            8º</span></b><span lang="EN-US" style="font-size: 10.0pt; line-height: 120%; font-family: Arial; color: #570E0A"> 
            The cork can be held with the ring and little fingers of the hand in 
            charge of holding the glass. </span></p>
            <p class="MsoNormal" style="text-align: justify; line-height: 120%">
            <b>
            <span lang="EN-US" style="font-size: 10.0pt; line-height: 120%; font-family: Arial; color: #570E0A">
            9º</span></b><span lang="EN-US" style="font-size: 10.0pt; line-height: 120%; font-family: Arial; color: #570E0A"> 
            When serving the glass of cider, if the thumb is retrieved from the 
            glass it makes picking it up easier. </span></p>
            <p class="MsoNormal" style="text-align: justify; line-height: 120%">
            <b>
            <span lang="EN-US" style="font-size: 10.0pt; line-height: 120%; font-family: Arial; color: #570E0A">
            10º</span></b><span lang="EN-US" style="font-size: 10.0pt; line-height: 120%; font-family: Arial; color: #570E0A"> 
            The pourer must always make sure the cider froths. </span></p>
            <h2>
            <span lang="EN-US" style="font-size: 10.0pt; font-family: Arial; color: #570E0A">
            Cider care</span></h2>
            <p class="MsoBodyText" style="text-align:justify">
            <span lang="EN-US" style="font-size: 10.0pt; font-family: Arial; color: #570E0A">
            It is similar to that of the wine.</span></p>
            <p class="MsoNormal" style="text-align: justify; line-height: 120%">
            <span lang="EN-US" style="font-size: 10.0pt; line-height: 120%; font-family: Arial; color: #570E0A">
            Avoid shaking the cider.</span></p>
            <p class="MsoNormal" style="text-align: justify; line-height: 120%">
            <span lang="EN-US" style="font-size: 10.0pt; line-height: 120%; font-family: Arial; color: #570E0A">
            The cider must be cool not cold, the ideal cider temperature is 
            between the 12-14&#730;C, it is therefore convenient to keep it in cool 
            water and always avoiding that the Cork goes into contact with the 
            water.</span></p>
            <p class="MsoBodyText2">
            <span lang="EN-US" style="font-size: 10.0pt; font-family: Arial; color: #570E0A">
            The cider must not be aged.</span></p>
            <p class="MsoNormal" style="line-height: 120%"><b>
            <span lang="EN-US" style="font-size: 10.0pt; line-height: 120%; font-family: Arial; color: #570E0A">
            CIDER DEFECTS</span></b></p>
            <p class="MsoBodyText2">
            <span lang="EN-US" style="font-size: 10.0pt; font-family: Arial; color: #570E0A">
            The natural cider is a living element that is subject to interact 
            with diverse microorganisms, normally lactic bacteria can produce 
            alterations in the cider quality. This can happen due to undesired 
            reactions or wrong oenological practices produced throughout the 
            production process. The most common are: </span></p>
            <p class="MsoNormal" style="text-align: justify; line-height: 120%">
            <b><i>
            <span lang="EN-US" style="font-size: 10.0pt; line-height: 120%; font-family: Arial; color: #570E0A">
            Acetified</span></i></b><span lang="EN-US" style="font-size: 10.0pt; line-height: 120%; font-family: Arial; color: #570E0A">. 
            High levels of volatile acidity generated normally by action of 
            lactic bacteria. To avoid this it is necessary to keep the PH levels 
            low. </span></p>
            <p class="MsoNormal" style="text-align: justify; line-height: 120%">
            <b><i>
            <span lang="EN-US" style="font-size: 10.0pt; line-height: 120%; font-family: Arial; color: #570E0A">
            Oily.</span></i></b><span lang="EN-US" style="font-size: 10.0pt; line-height: 120%; font-family: Arial; color: #570E0A"> 
            The activation of certain lactic bacteria generates polysaccharides 
            that infer the cider a slimy character.</span></p>
            <p class="MsoNormal" style="text-align: justify; line-height: 120%">
            <b><i>
            <span lang="EN-US" style="font-size: 10.0pt; line-height: 120%; font-family: Arial; color: #570E0A">
            Fruited.</span></i></b><span lang="EN-US" style="font-size: 10.0pt; line-height: 120%; font-family: Arial; color: #570E0A"> 
            In accordance to the studies carried out up until the moment it is 
            estimated that this alteration is due to n increase of acrolein 
            generated by lactic bacteria.</span></p>
            <p class="MsoNormal" style="text-align: justify; line-height: 120%">
            <b><i>
            <span lang="EN-US" style="font-size: 10.0pt; line-height: 120%; font-family: Arial; color: #570E0A">
            Turbity:</span></i></b><span lang="EN-US" style="font-size: 10.0pt; line-height: 120%; font-family: Arial; color: #570E0A"> 
            In addition to the loss of sparkle due to diverse colloidal 
            phenomena, this can also be produced due to the excessive use of 
            pears, because of its fibrous texture.</span></p>
            <p><b><i>
            <span lang="EN-US" style="font-size: 10.0pt; font-family: Arial; color: #570E0A">
            Potassium sorbate:</span></i></b><span lang="EN-US" style="font-size: 10.0pt; font-family: Arial; color: #570E0A"> 
            This defect occurs when its use (of permissible limits) is abusive, 
            capturing some spicy and aggressive notes.</span></p>
